		<section>
			<section.front>
				<doc.title toc-guid="Id71ff01c682311ea83aee46e6decbb85">
					<head parent="doc.title">
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<label.name>§ </label.name>
						<label.designator>8:18.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Handwriting evidence</headtext>
						<eos/>
						<eop/>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Scientific evidence to identify handwriting is admissible if the expert witness bases his opinion on recognized scientific techniques concerning spacing, shading, ink, and other characteristics. <eos/>
						<bos/>He may testify about whether a disputed writing and a genuine writing were done by the same individual and about tracing or alterations without comparison.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7950796074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>The lay witness may testify that he knows or recognizes the handwriting,[<footnote.reference refid="I7950a07074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] but he cannot state an opinion based on comparison of the writings.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7950a07174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>The expert witness may use crayon drawings, enlarged photographs, magnifying glasses, and other materials to illustrate for the jury the basis of his opinion.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7950a07274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>The jury may also compare the two writings. <eos/>
						<bos/>
						<cite.query w-src-number="0287017143" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-9-901" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Iefe8152074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-9-901(b)(3)</cite.query> requires that handwriting specimens that the trier of fact or an expert witness will compare shall be furnished to the opposite party no later than 10 days prior to trial.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7950a07374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>An expert who conducted a forensic accounting may testify that there are significant discrepancies as to checks written from a particular account. <eos/>
						<bos/>In this case, the accountant was trained to look for things that were odd or suspicious, including discrepancies in signatures.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7950a07474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Also, handwriting evidence is not required in every case where a written document is offered so long as there is other evidence, circumstantial or otherwise, to make a prima facie showing of authenticity.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7950c78074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
			</section.body>
